    "summary": "The satrapy system was the administrative framework through which the Achaemenid Persian Empire governed its vast territories — stretching from the Aegean to the Indus — through appointed regional governors (satraps) who collected tribute, maintained order, administered justice, and commanded local military forces while remaining accountable to the Great King. Darius I formalized the system into approximately 20–30 satrapies, each assessed a fixed annual tribute in silver or kind.\n\nThe satrap held quasi-royal authority within their province, often maintaining elaborate courts modeled on the Persian royal court. To check their power, Darius instituted parallel oversight: royal secretaries and military commanders reported directly to the king, and the 'King's Eyes and Ears' (royal inspectors) conducted periodic audits. Despite these controls, powerful satraps periodically revolted — the [[event:1221|Revolt of the Satraps]] (366–360 BC) showed the system's structural weakness. The satrapy system became the model for later Persian and Hellenistic provincial administration; Alexander the Great retained Persian satraps in many provinces after his conquest, and the Seleucid and Parthian empires both adapted versions of it.",
